# **Abstract** {#abstract}

	The purpose of the final project is to establish a decentralized network system for cryptocurrency, a blockchain system for users' transactions. To ensure the decentralized network, a peer-to-peer communication environment was implemented within nodes which validate both blockchains. Along with the blockchain mechanism, a few microservices were combined together to accomplish the fully functioning backend of the system. Each component will be further explained below with their flow/structure diagrams. The static frontend was used to collect the users’ inputs and to display the results of the processed data from the backend. The Azure cloud was used to deploy the application to the public so that users can interact via public URL link. 

# 

# **Introduction** {#introduction}

The goal of the project was to provide a URL link to the public which users can interact with the application by accessing through it. The application was first built in the local environment using the localhost address then it was deployed to Azure cloud upon its success.   
The backend of the application is responsible for the blockchain mechanism which contains FastAPI server, gRPC server/client, Kafka producer/consumer, and postgreSQL. Each component is described below in the Relationship to Other Work section. Upon its successful build, it was deployed to Azure cloud using the Azure Kubernetes Service.   
The frontend of the project is responsible for collecting the user inputs for the transaction request, and displaying the returning results from the backend. The problem that I encountered during the process of deploying to Azure web app service was that it automatically generated the HTTPS URL link which cannot be directed with the HTTP domain addresses. The backend, however, generated the HTTP type domain address for FastAPI server. To counter this issue, the httpsOnly feature was disabled so that the frontend can be accessed using the HTTP type as well.    
Multiple services in the kubernetes sometimes lose their connection which causes the blockchain to not get properly broadcasted or listened to by peer nodes. If the next transaction is processed properly, it displays the properly shared blockchain for each node.   

# **Main body of work**  {#main-body-of-work}

***This section will describe in details how the application was performed and executed in steps:***  
*Precondition:* 

- *Assume that both Azure Web App and Kubernetes services are running in Azure cloud properly. This enables the postgreSQl which allows to create the necessary tables in the database and initialize the initial values for each variable, and opens Kafka service which allows setting the producers and following consumers.*   
- *The nodes are already executed and each node gets the genesis block in the chain.*   
- *Make sure HTTP domain URL is used instead of HTTPS for the frontend URL link.*

Flow of the execution: 

1) Users access the application using the URL generated by the Azure web app. Following is the URL link: [http://892finalfrontend-cyh0f2hgaadeghf0.canadacentral-01.azurewebsites.net/](http://892finalfrontend-cyh0f2hgaadeghf0.canadacentral-01.azurewebsites.net/)	  
   If the error related to the backend communication occurs, please check the URL once again and check whether HTTP is used, not HTTPS.   
2) Users can type in the inputs in the corresponding input boxes and press the Send Transaction button after.   
3) The transaction data is then delivered to the backend using the fastAPI endpoint /transaction. Upon receiving the data, it sets the kafka\_producer and sends the transaction info to it under the topic of Transaction.   
4) When the kafka\_consumer listens to the incoming data, it first chooses which node to process with. It randomly chooses the node from the two and disables the unselected node.   
5) The chosen node processes the transaction. It first saves the transaction to the global variable. It then creates a new block, sets all of their internal variables, and it gets appended to the chain. Upon creation, the transaction gets saved to the database and both wallets are updated their balances.   
6) After finishing the process, it broadcasts the blockchain to the peer node using the gRPC client. The unselected node listens and replaces with its own blockchain with the received data to update with the new block only if the block is validated. The validation process is done by comparing the variable Previous Hash Code which the new block has with the actual previous block’s hash code.  
7) Server script collects the balance of both wallets, and blockchains in both nodes using the gRPC. It saves them into the dic format and returns to the frontend.  
8) The frontend then simply displays the results on the web page.   
9) On the top right corner, there is a button called Reset Blockchain. It resets all the values of the variables such as blockchains for each node, and wallet balances. 

# **Relation to other works**  {#relation-to-other-works}

***Each component in the application is described in detail regarding their job, responsibilities, and relationship to others.*** 

**React \+ Vita Script** 

- It provides a simple graphical user interface frontend.  
- Written in JSX file.   
- Collects user inputs, delivers to the backend, and displays the results returned from the backend. 


**FastAPI:**

- Receives users’ transaction request using the /transaction endpoint.   
- There are two endpoints in this application, /transaction POST and /reset POST. Endpoint /transaction process the blockchain mechanism with the received transaction information. It returns the updated balance of the user wallets and the full blockchain for both node1 and node2. 

**CORS:**

- Allows the frontend and the backend that have different origins to communicate via FastAPI endpoints.

**Nginx** 

- Force the web page so that it can be directed using HTTP.  
- However, it gets blocked by the Azure Web App policy. 

**Apache Kafka**: 

- A message broker which allows asynchronous communication.   
- Upon receiving the transaction info from the frontend through the FastAPI endpoint, it opens up the Kafka\_producer with the topic \= transaction.   
- Nodes, on the other hand, opens up the Kafka\_consumer which listens to the incoming transaction info. Upon receiving any, it determines which node to process the actual transaction process, updates the balances for both users’ wallets, create the new block with the transaction info, append the block the the chain, and broadcast the chain to the peer node. 

**gRPC**

- It is a server and client bidirectional communication protocol  
- Ensures the real-time communication between nodes to ensure the P2P network between nodes   
- Each node contains a server and a client which broadcasts to or listens from the peer. The selected node processes the transaction and broadcasts the blockchain to the peer and the unselected node listens to the broadcasts and updates its blockchain.

**Blockchain service** 

- Perform any blockchain logics   
- Logics includes following:  
  - Creating the genesis block   
  - Generating new block with the provided transaction info   
  - Validating & appending blockchain  
  - Updating users balance    
  - Hashing transactions   
  - Hashing block   
- Pop users transaction info from Kafka queue asynchronously (FIFO order). It is processed with the randomly selected node from two nodes   
- Updates the wallet balance in the postgreSQL

**Blockchain nodes** 

- gRPC server and client are used to broadcast or update the blockchain.   
- Each node utilizes the same blockchain mechanism located in blockchain.py script. 

**postgreSQL**

- Storing all the data including:  
  - Tables : transactions / wallets   
  - Initializing both wallets and their balance to 100  
  - Blockchain ledger for each node   
  - Initialize the users’ name as userA and user B.  
- Real-time data updating after each translation  

**Azure Cloud \- Web App Service** 

- React \+ Vita app deployment to the Azure web page service   
- Docker image deployed to the Azure resource repository. Web app uses this image to open up the Web App.

**Azure Cloud \- Azure Kubernetes Service**  

- Allows to generate one container using multiple images and resource services.   
- Two images, fast\_api and node, are deployed to the resource repository. These images are then configured using the yaml file. In the yaml file, not only these two images are configured, but other resource services are also configured.   
- In the yaml file, deployment and service sections were provided for each service and image.

# **Future Work**  {#future-work}

	Currently, the application only contains two nodes in the blockchain mechanism. In the common cryptography blockchain systems such as Bitcoin and Ethereum, miners act as the nodes that validate the chain of the transaction blocks. But in this project, two nodes are created and replaced by the miners. Also, the mining was not included to minimize the blockchain mechanism and focus more on the p2p environment within the nodes.   
	The FastAPI server is based on the HTTP domain which is the default policy for Azure Kubernetes Service policy. Thus, it could be transferred to HTTPS domain using the Ingress later on to enhance the security of the web page and the communication with the HTTPS frontend.

# **Conclusions** {#conclusions}

	The application successfully processed the requested blockchain transaction by a user, and it was deployed to Azure cloud which allowed a user to interact with the program using the shared public URL link. Although the application has much more space to improve, it meets the minimum requirements of setting the decentralized cloud system using more than 3 components.
